  "market_context": "Gold hourly price is trading inside a consolidation range, having already taken out the range high but not the range low. A reversal-style wick has formed, suggesting potential downside delivery, but the consolidation context lowers probability for an upside expansion attempt.",
  "key_observation": "On the 5-minute, price immediately fell through 50% of the wick rather than respecting it, signaling that the wick would not hold as support and that the consolidation low was the more likely draw on liquidity.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify on the hourly that price is in a consolidation range with the high already swept but the low still intact.",
    "Step 2: Note a wick has formed and consider whether price will respect 0.5 of the wick to trade higher, while acknowledging the consolidation context makes upside lower probability.",
    "Step 3: Drop down to the 5-minute timeframe to monitor whether 0.5 of the wick is respected as support.",
    "Step 4: Observe that as price opens, it immediately trades through 50% of the wick — disrespecting it.",
    "Step 5: Conclude that an expansion candle higher is unlikely within the time window since it would create too large a wick, so the consolidation low becomes the more probable draw.",
    "Step 6: Confirm the thesis as price expands lower and takes out the consolidation low."
  ],
  "outcome": "Consolidation low was taken out as anticipated after the wick was disrespected.",
  "lessons": "When price fails to respect 0.5 of a reversal wick on the lower timeframe, the wick is invalidated as support/resistance. In a consolidation, this disrespect signals the opposite side of the range is the more likely draw on liquidity.",
